The only non-terminal that can produce the terminal symbol ‘t21’ is NT20, and NT20 can do so only through the unit production  

  NT20 → ‘t21’.

NT20’s only other production is  

  NT20 → NT15 NT5,

which starts with whatever NT15 produces; that alternative can therefore never yield a string whose first token is ‘t21’.  
Consequently every occurrence of ‘t21’ in any sentence generated by the grammar must come from a separate NT20 that expands directly to ‘t21’ and produces no additional tokens.

The string to be checked contains two adjacent ‘t21’ tokens:

… t33  t21  t21  t33 …

To obtain two consecutive ‘t21’s, their parse must involve two distinct NT20s that are siblings in the same binary rule, i.e. some rule of the form

  X → NT20 NT20

so that the left NT20 yields the first ‘t21’ and the right NT20 yields the second, with nothing intervening.

Scanning the grammar shows that there is no production whose right-hand side is “NT20 NT20”.  
Without such a rule it is impossible for the grammar to place two NT20 expansions immediately next to each other, and therefore impossible to generate the substring “t21 t21”.

Because the target string contains that unattainable substring, it cannot be derived from the given grammar.
